  <glossary>
    <title>Glossary</title>
    <gi>
      <title>Affix</title>
      <p>A bound morpheme that attaches to a base; includes prefixes (before) and suffixes (after).</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>Allomorph</title>
      <p>One of two or more phonetic forms of a single morpheme (e.g., the plural morpheme has allomorphs /s/, /z/, and /ɪz/).</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>Base</title>
      <p>The morpheme that carries the core meaning of a word; the element to which affixes attach. Also called the root.</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>Bound morpheme</title>
      <p>A morpheme that cannot stand alone as a word; must be attached to another morpheme.</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>Compound</title>
      <p>A word formed by combining two or more free morphemes.</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>Free morpheme</title>
      <p>A morpheme that can stand alone as an independent word.</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>Morpheme</title>
      <p>The smallest unit of language that carries meaning.</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>Morphology</title>
      <p>The branch of linguistics that studies word structure and word formation.</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>Prefix</title>
      <p>An affix that attaches before the base.</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>Productive</title>
      <p>Describes a morphological pattern that speakers actively use to create new words.</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>Suffix</title>
      <p>An affix that attaches after the base.</p>
    </gi>
    <gi>
      <title>Suppletion</title>
      <p>The use of an entirely different word form to express a grammatical contrast (e.g., <em>go/went</em>).</p>
    </gi>
  </glossary>

